A '''critical vocabulary''' is a formal [[terminology]] related to one or more branches of [[critical theory]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}} Although it may be considered a type of [[jargon]], it is predominantly used by [[academic]]s {{Who|date=February 2018}} and is not [[slang]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}} The word "critical", as used in the term ''critical vocabulary'', takes on two meanings: "of essential importance" and "of or pertaining to [[critic]]s or [[criticism]]."{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}} Thus, the vocabulary is of essential importance to the critical theory that employs it and is used by that critical theory in order to produce [[criticism]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}
==Usage== Unlike the term ''jargon'', the term ''critical vocabulary'' is seldom used as a [[collective noun]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}} It is typically preceded by the [[definite article|definite]] or [[indefinite article]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}} When speaking about more than one critical theory, it is used in the plural (i.e. "the critical vocabularies of postmodern studies").{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}
==Criticism== Several people have criticized critical vocabularies as tools of alienation or obfuscation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.www.tuftsdaily.com/media/storage/paper856/news/2005/04/22/Features/Has-Academic.Jargon.Finally.Gone.Too.Far-1490971.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-05-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20110807012651/http://media.www.tuftsdaily.com/media/storage/paper856/news/2005/04/22/Features/Has-Academic.Jargon.Finally.Gone.Too.Far-1490971.shtml |archivedate=2011-08-07 |df= }}{{Failed verification|date=February 2018}} </ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.case.edu/webdev/2006/03/23/beware_of_your_vocabulary |title=Beware of your vocabulary: Web Development Blog: Creative Services: Marketing and Communications: Case Western Reserve University |publisher=Blog.case.edu |date=2006-03-23 |accessdate=2013-04-04}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=February 2018}} Also there have been assertions that the relatively recent proliferation of critical vocabularies has resulted in redundancy of both terms and ideas.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Evans|first1=William W.|year=1977|title=Language and the lay linguist|journal=American Speech|volume=52|issue=1/2|pages=134–145 |doi=10.2307/454728 |last2=Newman |first2=Edwin |last3=Mueller |first3=Robert K.|jstor=454728}}</ref>{{Failed verification|date=February 2018}} See the Pitfalls section under [[jargon]].
